## DaaS App-Sec Governance & DevSecOps Platform Manual
DevSecOps-as-a-Service (DaaS) removes the operational headache of setting up CI/CD tools, provisioning infrastructure, handling backups, and keeping up with monitoring. This centralized NetApp team provides mature, ready-to-use DevSecOps pipelines. Instead of taking months to integrate security tools like Coverity and Black Duck yourself, DaaS provides these out of the box.
------------------------------
## 1. Supported Platform Integrations
DaaS provides pre-configured integrations with standard development and security tools:

* Source Code Management (SCM): Perforce (BigTop), Bitbucket (BigTop & OpenLab), and GitHub (OpenLab).
* Security & Vulnerability Scanners: Coverity (Static Analysis), Black Duck (Compositional/License Scan), SonarQube, and Tenable Nessus.
* Artifact Registries: JFrog Artifactory (Docker and Helm registries).

------------------------------
## 2. Synopsys Detect (Black Duck) Integration
DaaS comes pre-installed with the Synopsys Detect Plugin. It scans your project's code base to identify open-source components, manage licenses, and discover security vulnerabilities.
## 2.1. Available Network Instances

* Production Instance: https://blackduck.eng.netapp.com
* Staging Instance: https://blackduck-staging.eng.netapp.com
* Project & User Creation Contact: Open a help ticket via enghelp+blackduck@netapp.com.

## 2.2. Required Black Duck User Roles
To run a scan, your Black Duck account API token must have these access roles:

| Role | Action Scope |
|---|---|
| Project Creator | Creates new Black Duck projects. |
| Project Code Scanner | Populates the project Bill of Materials (BOM). |
| Global Code Scanner | Populates the project BOM, checks for policy violations, and generates reports. |
| Project Manager | Downloads and manages project reports. |

## 2.3. Configuring the Plugin in Jenkins
Configure your plugin connections by navigating to Manage Jenkins ➔ Configure System ➔ Synopsys Detect:

   1. Global Download Strategy: Select Install AirGapped Detect as a Tool Installation (SecLab) or Download via scripts or use DETECT_JAR (Open EngLab).
   2. Black Duck URL: Enter your target server address (Staging or Production).
   3. Black Duck Credentials: Click Add ➔ Jenkins.
   * For API Tokens, change the Kind field to Secret text and paste your token into the Secret box.
      * For standard setups, use Username with password. Note: SAML is not supported.
   4. Advanced Settings: You can specify custom values for connection timeouts (defaults to 120 seconds) and check Trust Black Duck certificates to allow SSL handshakes.
   5. Click Test Connection to Black Duck to confirm a Connection successful! status displays, then click Save.

## 2.4. Generating Pipeline Syntax

   1. Go to the Pipeline Syntax helper page in your Jenkins pipeline job.
   2. Select synopsys_detect: Synopsys Detect from the Sample Step dropdown menu.
   3. Add your custom Detect configuration properties.
   4. Check Return status code or configure a Custom download strategy if needed.
   5. Click Generate Pipeline Script to get the exact code snippet for your Jenkinsfile.

